<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Adrianne Goodman 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 CLASS ACT: Friends and colleagues remembered Thomas G. Lakin on Sunday as a 
man who dedicated his entire career to education. . . . The popular chancellor 
of the Ventura County Community College District died Sunday (A1), the first 
known fatality from the so-called flesh-eating bacteria in California. . . . 
"He was a visionary," said Elise Schneider, president of Oxnard College (B1). 
"He cared for people in our district and was a tremendous leader." 
</P>
<P>
 TREES, PLEASE: The pumpkin patches that took up vacant lots and fields around 
the county are giving way to Christmas trees. . . . And not a moment too soon 
for those eager to embrace the season. In Ojai, where the Bower Tree Farm 
opened over the long Thanksgiving weekend, business has taken off at a good 
clip. "It started slow, but people are really starting to come in," said 
Marilyn Bower, whose family has run the five-acre site for 25 years. . . . 
Nationwide, more than 34 million trees are expected to be sold by Christmas 
Day. 
</P>
<P>
 SAND BLAST: Once, the water in Mugu Lagoon was deep enough to allow U. S. Navy 
boats to maneuver, but no longer. . . . Now, about 240 million tons a year of 
sand and silt are pouring into the lagoon from a series of creeks and arroyos 
(B1). A report says the fresh-water infusion is threatening habitat in Southern 
California's largest remaining salt marsh. . . . But don't rush out to see the 
lagoon -- you'll need special Navy permission, a restriction that the report 
recommends be relaxed. 
</P>
<P>
 GETTING YOUNGER?: Oxnard leads the county's 10 cities in birthrates, according 
to a recent study (B1). . . . Birthrates were lowest in Thousand Oaks, Simi 
Valley and Camarillo. . . . That's right in line with recent state figures 
showing that only 7.7% of Oxnard residents are senior citizens. In Moorpark -- 
another city with higher birth rates -- just 3.8% of residents are over the age 
of 65. . . . Looks as if the crunch for space in some of the county's schools 
won't end any time soon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
