<HEADLINE>
<P>
BROWN LEAVES REDSKINS OUT IN COLD; NFC: GIANT QUARTERBACK PASSES FOR TWO 
TOUCHDOWNS AND RUNS FOR ANOTHER IN A DRIVING RAIN DURING 21-19 VICTORY OVER 
WASHINGTON. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In the muddy depths of the NFC East, Dave Brown and the New York Giants 
withstood a cold, driving rainstorm for a victory. 
</P>
<P>
 Brown passed for two touchdowns and ran for another Sunday in the Giants' 
21-19 victory over the Washington Redskins. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the second consecutive victory for the Giants (5-7) after a seven-game 
losing streak during which Brown lost his job to Kent Graham. 
</P>
<P>
 Last week, Brown started against Houston but a concussion forced him out and 
Graham led the team to a 13-10 victory. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm happy that the team got the monkey off its back last week," said Brown. 
"This week, I got the monkey off my back. I haven't had a win since the last 
time we played Washington." 
</P>
<P>
 Brown, who led the Giants to a 31-23 victory over Washington on Sept. 18, 
completed 10 of 17 passes for 161 yards. 
</P>
<P>
 The Redskins (2-10) failed to get anything going, scoring their points on four 
field goals by Chip Lohmiller and a 60-yard fumble return by Martin Bayless. 
</P>
<P>
 The Redskins have lost 14 consecutive NFC East games and are 0-7 at home this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
 "For whatever reason, we don't make the plays when we have to," Redskin Coach 
Norv Turner said. "This is a very competitive level of football, and the New 
York Giants are capable of making plays. When you're in this position, mistakes 
are things that end up costing you." 
</P>
<P>
 Brown connected on touchdown pass plays with Chris Calloway and Mike Sherrard. 
Rodney Hampton had 106 yards in 34 carries. 
</P>
<P>
 Rookie Heath Shuler, meanwhile, started for the Redskins for the first time 
since he sprained his ankle against Arizona on Oct. 16. 
</P>
<P>
 The rookie began poorly -- he was four of 14 for 69 yards and an interception 
in the first half -- and finished 11 of 28 for 165 yards. 
</P>
