<HEADLINE>
<P>
FALCONS OVERCOME WALKER'S 91-YARD RUN; NFC: GEORGE AND MATHIS ACCOUNT FOR TWO 
SCORES TO LEAD ATLANTA TO A 28-21 VICTORY OVER PHILADELPHIA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jeff George and Terance Mathis put a damper on Herschel Walker's return to 
Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
 George threw for 364 yards and combined with Mathis on two touchdown passes 
Sunday, giving Atlanta a 28-21 victory over Philadelphia despite a 91-yard 
touchdown run by Walker, who won a Heisman Trophy 12 years ago at Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
 Walker's run, longest from scrimmage in the NFL since Bo Jackson went 92 yards 
for the Raiders five years ago, gave the Eagles a 14-13 lead 2:45 into the 
second half. It came one play after Bill Romanowski intercepted a deflected 
pass to end what looked like an Atlanta scoring drive. 
</P>
<P>
 And it certainly could have deflated the Falcons, who have been troubled by 
internal strife, including the suspension of Andre Rison for a game. 
</P>
<P>
 But neither three interceptions nor the run seemed to bother George, who 
promptly marched the Falcons 67 yards in six plays, capping the drive with a 
seven-yard touchdown pass to Mathis, who finished with 10 receptions for 124 
yards. Then George passed to Mathis again for a two-point conversion that gave 
Atlanta a 21-14 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 "When something like that interception happens, it ticks you off, particularly 
when they come right back with a big play," said George, who completed 26 of 46 
passes but was booed for three interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
 "We showed character because we came right back and did what we had to do 
after we looked real ugly." 
</P>
<P>
 Offensive tackle Mike Kenn, who broke a Falcon record by playing in his 247th 
consecutive game, said: "We said to ourselves we'd already screwed up enough. 
Let's get it on." 
</P>
<P>
 They did. 
</P>
<P>
 The next time Atlanta got the ball, George took the Falcons 87 yards in 12 
plays, capped by a powerful five-yard run by Craig Heyward. Three completions 
on the drive were to Mathis, who has 90 for the season for 1,073 yards. 
</P>
<P>
 Philadelphia got one score back with 4:22 left on Walker's two-yard run, set 
up by Eric Allen's interception, the third thrown by George. 
</P>
<P>
 But rookie Anthony Phillips intercepted Randall Cunningham on the first play 
after Philadelphia got the ball back with 2:25 to play on its 43. And the 
Eagles couldn't get a play off after Cunningham completed a 61-yard pass to 
Victor Bailey at the Atlanta 19 with 11 seconds and no timeouts left. 
</P>
</TEXT>
