<P>
SOUTHLAND PREVIEW / THE BUSINESS WEEK AHEAD: LOS ANGELES COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Unemployment Figures Due: When the November jobless rate reports come out 
Friday for Los Angeles County and the rest of the state, it should give 
analysts a clearer sense of just how solid the apparent economic recovery here 
really is. Reports have shown unemployment in the state declining sharply over 
the last three months and over the last two months in the county, even as 
separate surveys show California continuing to lose jobs.Many economists are 
skeptical that things are improving as much as the jobless figures suggest. 
Another month's figures, however, could help establish a true trend. In 
October, the jobless rate was 7.8% for the county, down from 8.3% in September 
and 10.3% in August. For the state, unemployment in October was 7.7%, 
continuing its decline from 9.0% in July. In the November figures, "If we don't 
get a little upward bounce (in the jobless rates), it means we really have 
something cooking," one economist said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
