<P>
BRIEFLY: MANUFACTURING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Machine Tool Orders Plunge: October orders for U.S. tools totaled $365.3 
million, down 29% from $514.6 million in September but 45.5% higher than in 
October, 1993, according to the Assn. for Manufacturing Technology. The trade 
group represents makers of tools that cut and shape metal for products ranging 
from appliances to airplanes.For the first 10 months of the year, machine tool 
orders totaled $3.71 billion, a 35.8% increase from the same period a year ago. 
Higher orders for machine tools tend to indicate that manufacturers are 
optimistic about sales. Analysts did not expect October's figures to compete 
with those of September, when the industry's most well-received trade show in 
at least a decade prompted a 57.2% increase in orders over August. 
</P>
